    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.35-36_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">35</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    Columbia University
                        <lb/>
                    in the City of New York
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps">DEPARTMENT OF ANTHROPOLOGY</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>March 18, 1932</dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                        
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just finished "Black Elk Speaks." <add>(</add>I want you to know that<add>)</add> <del>i</del><add>I</add>t makes me happy and sad all at once--sad for the days that are gone, and glad that a white man really lives who can enter into a right understanding of Dakota's vision, and can trasnlate<sic>translate</sic> it into so poetic a form.</p>
                
                <p>Why should it makeso<sic>make so</sic> much difference to me? I will tell you. Because my grandfather, a chief, was a medicine man among the Yankton and saved many lives through his teaching from his vision. And my father, also a chief-(-who renounced his office in favor of his best friend, to become a Christian clergyman after "the end of the dream" when it was apparent to him that he could <del/><add><unclear>do</unclear></add> nothing under the old regime for his people and he thought he must try to train himself to lead them under the new conditions)-- respected and revered those things <add>(</add>of which <add>here</add> you have<add>)</add> written, and told and taught<del/> them to us his children as a sacred heritage. I have in my 
                
                <note type="recipient">(over)</note>
                 
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.35-36_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">36</fw>
                
                    texts collected for anthropological studies not a few examples of different people's visions. I find them very inspiring--but I never knew until <del>k</del>now how their meaning could be expressed in such a way as to be understandable to people of such a mate<del><unclear>ial</unclear></del><add>ria</add>l civilization as this.</p>
                
                <p><add>(</add>Many thanks for your<add>) An</add> exquisite piece of work<add>!</add></p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>(M<del/><add>i</add>ss) Ella Cara Deloria</signed>
                    <signed>Ella Cara Deloria</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
